================================================================
CHAPTER 1: INTRODUCTION
================================================================

1.1 Background of the Study
Machine learning has become a practical approach for building predictive systems in education, business, healthcare, and engineering. Classification is one of the most common supervised learning tasks, where a model learns from labeled examples to predict unknown classes. In many real-world problems, a single model may perform well on one type of pattern and poorly on another. This is why ensemble learning is widely used: it combines predictions from multiple models to improve reliability and reduce model-specific bias.

In this project, three models are compared:
1. Decision Tree Classifier
2. K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)
3. Voting Ensemble (Decision Tree + KNN)

The project also studies outliers, which are unusual data points that can influence model behavior. Two outlier handling methods are implemented:
1. Z-score based outlier detection
2. Interquartile Range (IQR) based outlier detection

The project goal is not only to build classifiers, but also to evaluate how data cleaning choices affect model performance.

1.2 Problem Statement
Machine learning performance is sensitive to both model selection and data quality. Two practical problems are addressed:
1. A single model may not generalize consistently across all data patterns.
2. Outliers may reduce model accuracy or distort training boundaries.

Without controlled evaluation, it is difficult to determine:
1. Whether an ensemble approach outperforms individual models.
2. Which outlier removal strategy is beneficial for a specific dataset.

This project solves both issues in one pipeline and reports the comparative results.

1.3 Aim of the Project
The aim of this project is to develop and evaluate a voting ensemble classification system using Decision Tree and KNN models, while analyzing the impact of Z-score and IQR outlier removal on predictive performance.

1.4 Objectives of the Project
The specific objectives are:
1. To preprocess a classification dataset and separate features from target labels.
2. To detect and remove outliers using Z-score and IQR methods.
3. To train Decision Tree and KNN models on original and cleaned datasets.
4. To create a Voting Ensemble classifier from Decision Tree and KNN.
5. To compare all models using accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score.
6. To analyze the effect of outlier handling on each model.
7. To generate reproducible output artifacts (processed datasets, report file, and accuracy plot).

1.5 Scope of the Study
The scope of this study includes:
1. Binary classification task using tabular data.
2. Three model families (Decision Tree, KNN, Voting Ensemble).
3. Two outlier detection methods (Z-score and IQR) applied to numeric features only.
4. Standard train-test evaluation with configurable parameters.
5. Comparison of model performance across:
   - Original dataset
   - Z-score cleaned dataset
   - IQR cleaned dataset

Out of scope:
1. Deep learning models
2. Unsupervised learning methods
3. Hyperparameter optimization at large scale
4. Production deployment (API/cloud serving)

1.6 Significance of the Study
This project is significant because it demonstrates an end-to-end machine learning workflow that is useful for students and practitioners:
1. It shows a direct comparison between individual and ensemble learning.
2. It shows that outlier handling is not universally beneficial and must be tested.
3. It produces interpretable outputs that support decision-making.
4. It provides modular Python code suitable for extension in academic or applied settings.


