CHAPTER 2: LITERATURE REVIEW
================================================================

2.1 Introduction to Machine Learning
Machine learning is a branch of artificial intelligence where algorithms learn patterns from data to make predictions or decisions. A machine learning workflow typically includes data collection, cleaning, feature preparation, model training, and evaluation. Performance is influenced by dataset quality, algorithm choice, and validation strategy.

In classification tasks, the model predicts discrete class labels. Common examples include pass/fail prediction, fraud detection, disease diagnosis, and sentiment categorization.

Core concepts relevant to this project:
1. Generalization: model performance on unseen data.
2. Bias-variance tradeoff: simple models may underfit; complex models may overfit.
3. Data preprocessing: missing value handling, encoding, scaling, and outlier management.
4. Evaluation metrics: accuracy alone may not be enough in imbalanced settings.

2.2 Supervised Learning
Supervised learning uses labeled examples to learn a mapping from inputs (features) to outputs (targets). This project uses two supervised classifiers:

Decision Tree:
1. Learns recursive feature splits.
2. Produces interpretable decision rules.
3. Handles non-linear feature interactions.
4. Can overfit if not constrained.

K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN):
1. Instance-based model.
2. Predicts class using nearest data points in feature space.
3. Sensitive to feature scaling and noise.
4. Often performs well when local neighborhoods are informative.

Voting Ensemble:
1. Combines base classifier predictions.
2. Soft voting uses class probabilities and averages confidence.
3. Can reduce variance and improve robustness when base learners are complementary.

2.3 Machine Learning in Education
Educational systems produce rich data such as attendance, quiz scores, assignment records, and engagement logs. Machine learning can support:
1. Early warning systems for at-risk learners.
2. Personalized academic support recommendations.
3. Course-level analytics for quality improvement.
4. Resource allocation and intervention planning.

In education-focused datasets, outliers may appear due to data entry issues, exceptional student behavior, or unusual course conditions. Removing outliers blindly can hide meaningful cases; retaining all outliers can reduce model stability. Therefore, comparing model performance before and after outlier treatment is practically important.


